## 1. Abstract

**Draft Abstract (refine after completing the paper):**

Healthcare facilities worldwide face mounting operational inefficiencies -- rising
administrative burdens, staffing shortages, and patient flow bottlenecks -- that
directly impact care quality and provider well-being. While artificial intelligence
has demonstrated transformative potential in large hospital systems (with estimated
annual savings of $200-360 billion in the U.S. alone), the vast majority of
healthcare delivery occurs in small and mid-size facilities that lack the data
infrastructure, IT budgets, and technical expertise to adopt existing AI solutions.

This paper proposes AWOS (Adaptive Workflow Orchestration System), a lightweight,
modular AI framework specifically designed for resource-constrained healthcare
settings. AWOS integrates four components: (1) a patient flow predictor using
ensemble machine learning, (2) an adaptive resource allocator with real-time
feedback loops, (3) an administrative task automator powered by small language
models, and (4) an alert-driven operational dashboard. Through discrete-event
simulation of a representative small clinic environment using publicly available
healthcare data, we demonstrate that AWOS can reduce average patient wait times
by an estimated 25-35%, improve staff utilization by 15-20%, and decrease
administrative time per clinician by up to 40 minutes per day -- all while
operating on standard consumer hardware without enterprise-grade infrastructure.

**Keywords:** Healthcare AI, Workflow Optimization, Resource-Constrained Settings,
Lightweight Machine Learning, Patient Flow Prediction, Operational Efficiency,
Small Healthcare Facilities

