## 3. Literature Review

### 3.1 AI for Hospital Operations (Large-Scale Systems)

The application of AI to hospital operations has matured significantly. Key works
include:

**Predictive Operations Management:**
- An AI-driven framework combining XGBoost and LSTM models for patient demand
  forecasting demonstrated substantial improvements in simulated hospital
  environments: bed utilization increased from 73% to 88%, staff idle time
  reduced by 15%, and surgery scheduling conflicts decreased by 23%
  (International Journal of Professional Business Review, 2025).
- These models, however, require rich historical data streams that small
  facilities rarely possess.

**Patient Flow and ED Prediction:**
- Machine learning models for ED overcrowding prediction have achieved MAE of
  4.19 (TSiTPlus model) for hourly predictions and 2.00 (XCMPlus) for daily
  predictions (JMIR Medical Informatics, 2025).
- Patient arrival prediction using XGBoost achieves MAPE of 5.03-14.1% across
  11 international ED datasets (BMC Medical Informatics, 2024).
- Random Forest achieves MAE of 2.70-3.29 for outpatient department predictions
  (Indian Journal of Science and Technology, 2025).

**AI Triage Systems:**
- DeepTriage achieves 92.6% triage accuracy using hybrid neural networks,
  compared to 76.4-79.2% for traditional protocols, reducing decision time
  from 187-245 seconds to 14.8 seconds (Pinnacle Academic Press, 2025).
- ED-Triage-Agent uses multi-agent AI for collaborative emergency department
  triage (medRxiv, 2026).

### 3.2 Multi-Agent AI in Healthcare

Multi-agent AI systems represent a frontier in healthcare AI:

- Orchestrated multi-agent systems maintain 90.6% accuracy at batch sizes of 5
  tasks and 65.3% at 80 tasks, while single-agent accuracy collapses from
  73.1% to 16.6% under the same workloads. Multi-agent approaches also use
  up to 65-fold fewer tokens (Nature, npj Health Systems, 2026).
- MMedAgent-RL uses reinforcement learning for dynamic multi-agent medical
  reasoning, achieving 23.6% average performance gain over strong baselines
  (Microsoft Research, 2026).
- Randomized controlled trials (n=70 clinicians) show collaborative AI
  workflows improve diagnostic accuracy from 75% baseline to 82-85%
  (Nature, npj Digital Medicine, 2026).

### 3.3 Lightweight ML for Resource-Constrained Environments

A growing body of work demonstrates that lightweight models can achieve
competitive performance:

- A lightweight ECG classifier achieves 99.34% accuracy with only 692K
  parameters (2.64 MB), enabling real-time cardiac monitoring on wearable
  edge devices (Scientific Reports, 2026).
- Malaria classification using classical ML achieves 97.15% accuracy with
  only 1.2-2.3 kB model size, outperforming deep learning models requiring
  13.6-44.7 MB (arXiv, 2025).
- An arrhythmia detection model achieves 98.44% accuracy with 8.54 KB model
  size and 0.46 microsecond inference latency (arXiv, 2026).

### 3.4 No-Show Prediction and Appointment Optimization

- A 2025 study across 15 family medicine clinics (1M+ appointments, 109K
  patients) achieved AUROC of 0.85 for no-show prediction and 0.92 for late
  cancellation prediction using gradient boosting (Annals of Family Medicine,
  2025).
- Lead time (days between booking and appointment) emerged as the single most
  important predictor -- appointments booked 60+ days in advance carry
  significantly higher no-show risk.
- No-show rates in primary care typically range from 15-30%, representing
  enormous wasted capacity in small clinics where each slot matters more.

### 3.5 Identified Gap in Literature

| Dimension | Existing Research | Gap |
|---|---|---|
| Target Setting | Large hospitals, academic medical centers | Small/mid-size clinics, rural facilities |
| Data Requirements | Large EHR databases (65K+ patients) | Minimal data (hundreds of patients) |
| Infrastructure | Enterprise cloud, dedicated IT teams | Standard consumer hardware |
| Model Complexity | Deep learning, transformer models | Lightweight ensemble methods |
| System Scope | Single-task (triage OR scheduling OR flow) | Unified orchestration across multiple tasks |
| Adaptiveness | Static models retrained periodically | Real-time adaptive feedback loops |
| Cost Analysis | Rarely addressed | Central to value proposition |

**This paper addresses all six dimensions of this gap simultaneously.**

